<TEXT>
leanne patton a 16yearold 
protestant had never met a roman catholic until she went to a 
memorial service for the victims of an ira bombing and ended up 
holding hands with two nuns 
that moment at st annes cathedral in belfast when the minister 
asked everyone in the overflowing congregation to join hands and 
pray marked a turning point in leannes life 
she had been crying for the 11 people killed in enniskillen on 
nov 8 1987 and was so wrapped up in the service she didnt realize 
she had picked up the hands of two nuns who were sitting beside her 
i went home and i thought im just really fed up that i have 
to hate this woman because shes wearing a nuns habit i have to 
hate this fellow because hes a catholic it just went over and 
over in my mind you know what am i going to do she said 
id never met any catholics never never my mom and dad 
are very good they really are they didnt keep me away from 
catholics its just where i lived there werent any she said 
in northern ireland with its history of sectarian animosities 
it is common for youngsters and even adults never to have met 
someone of another religion 
many of northern irelands 1 million protestants and 600000 
catholics live in neighborhoods segregated along religious lines 
and all but 1000 of the provinces 350000 children attend schools 
that are almost entirely protestant or catholic 
leanne is studying for college entrance exams at mainly 
protestant grosvenor high school in east belfast 
after the enniskillen memorial service she decided to try to 
arrange an exchange with a catholic high school 
i never thought it would be anything big just a small 
meeting leanne said i was a very quiet person but 
something inside of me said i think you should really advertise 
this and before i knew what i was saying i asked if i could 
address the school assembly 
well i went and did that assembly and they clapped and they 
clapped and i was just shocked i didnt think anybody felt the same 
way i did and there were hundreds of them they said this is 
the right thing were doing 
the first exchange late last year was with a group of catholic 
students from two schools our lady of mercy and st patricks 
as the grosvenor students waited for the catholics to arrive 
leanne said they were literally trying to think what these 
catholics were going to look like are they going to talk funny and 
what are their names going to be like 
because wed never met we just had these ideas about the other 
side and then when we came together we just realized they were 
just like us 
over the past year the students have exchanged further visits 
friendships have grown outside school with frequent visits to local 
discos restaurants and the movies and shared stays at a 
governmentsponsored camp 
the grosvenor girls have also participated in a play bridges 
of celebration with boys from corpus christi college a catholic 
secondary school in west belfast an irish republican army 
stronghold it filled the opera house in belfast and will be 
performed again in dublin in february 
recalling the first rehearsal on neutral ground at queens 
university in belfast leanne said 
when they first walked in they just sat down and stared at 
you i said oh dear whats this going to be like but then we 
got to know them and we realized they were great 
she has no illusions that her activities will change the country 
no way im never going to become a catholic and none of them are 
ever going to become a protestant just because theyve met she 
said 
but just the fact that we are meeting and becoming friends 
it is harder to hate someone if you know them 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

