<TEXT>
the bush administration will have its hands 
full trying to cap medicares spending spiral without cutting into 
the quality of health care the program provides to 32 million 
americans says outgoing health and human services secretary otis r 
bowen 
one the reasons its going to be tougher is because of the 
massive new numbers of old people that we have coming along bowen 
said 
with overall medicare costs growing at about twice the rate of 
inflation bowen said the 100 billion program is a natural place to 
look for savings 
at the same time we have to walk a very tight line and make 
sure we are not reducing the quality of care and access to care 
he said in an interview it is my judgment that were getting 
close to that level now and we have to be very cautious about going 
too deep 
bowen declined to discuss specifics of the final budget the 
reagan administration will submit next month but department sources 
have acknowledged agreeing to about 6 billion in net reductions in 
projected medicare outlays mostly by holding down payments to 
doctors and hospitals 
the physician portion of medicare part b is growing about 15 
percent a year and democrats and republicans alike in congress have 
said it will undergo close scrutiny in budget deliberations 
beyond the cuts he has agreed to for the next budget bowen said 
we are getting close to the time where further ratcheting down 
could cause some deterioration in the quality of care and perhaps 
even access to care 
bowen who will be 71 in february and plans to retire in indiana 
noted that projections call for the number of people over the age of 
100 to increase from 25000 to 100000 over the next decade 
not only will they tend to require more medical attention but 
many also will used up savings and might become a bigger burden 
on public assistance he said 
bowen a former twoterm governor of indiana who said running 
that state was easier than running the huge hhs department said his 
greatest accomplishment was getting president reagan to back a 
catastrophicillness insurance addition to medicare in the most 
sweeping expansion of the program since its birth two decades ago 
getting the presidents approval over the objections of so many 
in the cabinet that was the tough part said bowen once the 
president gave his approval then it became a lot easier to try to 
contain the number of additions congress wanted to add to it 
on the other hand bowen said he is disappointed he has been 
unable to get states to move more quickly to solve medical 
malpractice insurance problems which he said are threatening access 
to health care in some regions 
he said the bush administration should be ready to introduce 
federal legislation to override the states on the issue unless they 
move quickly bowen said he was not suggesting such a step during 
the coming year but certainly within four years unless the 
states act 
bowen said there is a remaining need for special emphasis on aids 
because of the emotional response of the people people are scared 
to death 
i hesitate to single it out as a disease to be treated 
differently from others but i think as yet it does need to have a 
little extra special treatment he said 
bowen said he has not been consulted by bush transition officials 
for a recommendation on who should succeed him but he said he hopes 
the incoming president will not view the appointment as minor 
when youre talking about a kinder and gentler america youre 
talking about hhs he said of the huge agency that has a larger 
budget than the pentagon and embraces such programs as social 
security medicare and welfare 
the department also includes the sprawling public health service 
umbrella that covers such wellknown agencies as the food and drug 
administration the national institutes of health and the centers 
for disease control 
bowen said he hopes bush will give the new hhs secretary 
authority to pick the heads of those major agencies 
i think loyalty is one of the most important attributes of 
somebody who is working for you and the appointing authority sort of 
draws that loyalty he said i think you can get a lot more 
accomplished and better serve the public if you have a team rather 
than somebody who you never knew and never worked with maybe you 
wouldnt develop the confidence in them you should 
