<TEXT>
the 20 men and 12 women named american rhodes 
scholars represent 26 states and include a martial arts expert and a 
23yearold doctoral candidate who started college at age 12 
many of those awarded 1989 rhodes scholarships for two years of 
study at oxford university in england showed strong interest in 
using their education to battle aids poverty hunger and 
homelessness said david alexander american secretary of the rhodes 
scholarship trust 
the group includes students with aspirations in politics 
medicine and writing alexander said sunday adding that at least 
three worked to support themselves while attending college 
the scholarship recipients were chosen during meetings held 
nationwide wednesday and saturday 
four winners are from new york three from ohio and two from 
oklahoma 
harvard university had with five winners yale had four and 
stanford two 
one of the winners holly wyatt of san clemente works 20 hours a 
week as a waitress and squeezes in volunteer work with the meals on 
wheels organization for the needy while attending the university of 
southern california 
ms wyatt expects to graduate in may with a double major in 
political science and international relations with a minor in peace 
and conflict studies 
when i finish at oxford i would like to work at an 
international institution she said i would like to work in 
arms control like in western europeanunited states relations 
someday i think id like to teach college but id like to 
have some kind of effect on policy first she said 
another winner was gregory peter dubois who entered new college 
of the university of southern florida at age 12 dubois who has 
published numerous research papers in high energy physics expects 
to receive his doctoral degree from the california institute of 
technology next year 
another winner was barry uphoff who won first place in a 
seconddegree black belt taekwondo competition in 1986 and was 
ranked among the nations top 10 competitors in the martial arts 
field in 1986 and 1987 
uphoff a natural sciences and public health major at johns 
hopkins university in baltimore plans to study law at oxford before 
going to medical school 
the rhodes scholarships were established in 1902 by the estate of 
cecil rhodes a british philanthropist and colonialist he had hoped 
the scholarships would contribute to world understanding and peace 
among the qualities sought in scholars are proven intellectual 
and academic excellence integrity respect for others the ability 
to lead and use their talents fully 
scholarship winners will receive college and university fees and 
a stipend to cover living expenses 
women have been allowed to apply since 1976 
a total of 2532 american students who have received the 
scholarships since the program started in 1903 
to qualify scholars must be unmarried and between ages 18 and 24 
