the supreme court today upheld a voting rights 
ruling that led to the election of a black arkansas house member 
from crittenden county 
the court by an 80 vote ruled against an appeal by gov bill 
clinton and other arkansas officials that had challenged the 
election of ben mcgee as a state legislator 
the case began when blacks in crittenden county filed a voting 
rights lawsuit attacking the countys atlarge system for electing 
two house members 
the suit contended that the system deprived black voters of a 
chance to elect a black to the house 
a special threejudge federal court agreed last april that the 
system violated the federal voting rights act 
the threejudge court threw out the results of a march 8 primary 
election in which mcgee who is black was defeated by james 
stockley who is white for the democratic nomination 
the lower court split the house voting district into two 
singlemember districts and on sept 20 mcgee won the nomination 
that was tantamount to election on nov 8 since no republican ran 
for the seat 
clinton and the other state officials said the federal court 
improperly threw out the results of the first primary and ordered a 
new election 
but the federal court said the voting rights law was violated 
although it did not find intentional discrimination against blacks 
the law does not require minority groups to prove intentional 
discrimination before getting courts to order election changes 
the threejudge court noted that there is ample evidence that 
black voters in crittenden county were deprived of a chance to elect 
one of their own it said its conclusion is supported by evidence of 
highly racially polarized voting 
one of the new singlemember districts created by the lower court 
has a population of more than 60 percent black 
todays decision not accompanied by any opinion upheld the 
threejudge court ruling justice william j brennan hospitalized 
last week for treatment of pneumonia did not participate in the 
vote 
the case is clinton vs smith 88554 
