the supreme court avoiding a decision on an 
important issue for all lawsuits alleging age bias in employment 
today dismissed the case of a laidoff pennsylvania man 
by an 81 vote the justices said in effect that they had made a 
mistake when agreeing to decide whether eugene f briecks lawsuit 
against his former employer harbisonwalker refractories should 
proceed to trial 
the courts action was carried in a onesentence unsigned 
decision dismissing the case as improvidently granted justice 
byron r white dissented 
the effect is to leave intact an appeals court victory for brieck 
that clears the way for further trial court proceedings in his case 
harbisonwalker a division of dresser industries sells 
specialized ceramic brick products primarily to steel producers 
brieck worked as an installation specialist for harbisonwalker from 
1965 to 1982 
in july 1982 several employees of harbisonwalkers iron and 
steel marketing support group were laid off including brieck he 
then was 55 
brieck sued in pittsburgh in 1984 contending that he was laid 
off and not recalled to work because of his age his lawsuit pointed 
to a 39yearold installation specialist with less seniority who was 
not laid off until november 1982 and then recalled eight months 
later 
lawyers for harbisonwalker contended that the other employee 
hugh faust was retained because of his more diverse work experience 
a federal judge threw out briecks suit ruling that 
harbisonwalker had articulated legitimate nondiscriminatory 
business reasons for laying off brieck while retaining a younger man 
with less seniority 
but the 3rd us circuit court of appeals reinstated the suit 
last year 
the appeals court ruled that an employer charged with violating 
the federal age discrimination in employment act cannot avoid trial 
by articulating legitimate business reasons if the suing employee 
presents a reasonable inference that the employers proffered 
explanation is unworthy of credence 
the appeals court added the question is not whether the 
employers asserted reason is plausible but whether there is also 
evidence of record which if credited could render the reason 
implausible 
lawyers for harbisonwalker had argued in a session before the 
justices oct 31 that the appeals court ruling would virtually 
eliminate pretrial dismissals in employment discrimination cases 
the case is harbisonwalker vs brieck 87271 
