<TEXT>
the supreme court in a ruling likely to mean 
millions of additonal dollars for some hospitals today barred the 
government from retroactively applying rules limiting reimbursement 
paid to hospitals treating medicare patients 
by a 90 vote the court rejected reagan administration arguments 
that some hospitals could reap a windfall from a ban on retroactive 
application of the governments reimbursement formula 
the justices upheld a ruling that awarded more than 2 million to 
seven hospitals the administration said more money could be at 
stake 
the government in 1981 adopted a rule that excluded from the 
medicare reimbursement formula for private hospitals the wages paid 
by hospitals owned by the federal government 
the idea was to save money by not applying national pay scales to 
private hospitals in areas with lower wage levels 
but the department of health and human services adopted the new 
rule without allowing a time for the public to comment on the 
proposal the formula was challenged by private hospitals and thrown 
out by a federal judge as a violation of proper rulemaking 
procedures 
the federal agency adopted the rule again in 1984 using the 
correct procedure but this time the department applied the rule 
retroactively to reimbursement sought by the hospitals beginning 
july 1 1981 
the supreme court today upheld a ruling by the us circuit court 
of appeals here that the formula may not be applied retroactively 
our interpretation of the medicare act compels the conclusion 
that the secretary of hhs has no authority to promulgate 
retroactive costlimit rules said justice anthony m kennedy for 
the court 
the hospitals involved in the case are georgetown university 
hospital and howard university hospital here tucson ariz 
general greater southeast community tucson medical center st 
cloud minn hospital and community hospital of battle creek mich 
the case is bowen vs georgetown university hospital 871097 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

