<TEXT>
the agriculture department will bar timber 
harvesting in certain parts of national forests in oregon and 
washington in order to broaden habitat protection for the spotted 
owl the chief of the forest service said monday 
f dale robertson said most of the new habitat areas will range 
from 1000 to 2000 acres in size and will serve as protection for 
nesting owls as well as providing stepping stones between larger 
areas totaling more than 16 million acres already protected as 
owl habitats 
in the olympic national forest the new habitat areas may be as 
large as 3000 acres each he said 
in all the special habitat areas are expected to reduce the 
annual timber harvest on national forests in oregon and washington 
by about 180 million board feet 
each of the 13 national forests that have owls will share in the 
linkage system the exact number will not be determined until the 
forests submit final management plans to ensure that spotted owl 
populations will be maintained 
this has been an extremely difficult decision to make but i 
believe it strikes a reasonable balance between the two conflicting 
goals of sustaining spotted owl populations and providing timber 
supplies that are vital to the economies of oregon and washington 
robertson said 
the forest service a usda agency has been embroiled in 
controversy concerning its management plans for spotted owl 
habitats notably in the pacific northwest where there are concerns 
that protection of the birds could adversely affect the timber 
industry 
however robertson said the controversy has not been confined to 
his agency noting that a lawsuit against interiors bureau of land 
management has resulted in an injunction prohibiting blm from 
harvesting mature timber on some lands the agency administers in 
oregon 
also the fish and wildlife service is being challenged in court 
over its 1987 refusal to designate the owl a threatened or 
endangered species 
meantime authorities in oregon voted last week to deny a place 
on the state list of endangered or threatened species to a 
robinsized seabird called the marbled murrelet after biologists 
were unable to determine the birds population 
we simply dont have good baseline data on the murrelets 
population size nor any trends indicating changes in that 
population said rod ingram chief of the wildlife division for 
the oregon fish and wildlife commission 
the oregon chapter of the audubon society and the oregon natural 
resources council had petitioned to place the bird on the list under 
the new oregon endangered species act last january 
