<TEXT>
the environmental protection agency and the 
states are not enforcing water pollution regulations against 150000 
drinking water sources serving 36 million travelers workers 
students and others drinking water outside the home according to an 
internal epa report released monday by a conservation group 
among these sources are those aboard trains buses and airplanes 
the report said 
the group the national wildlife federation said it planned to 
sue the epa over deficiencies in enforcement of the safe drinking 
water act the federation said it gave epa the required 60day 
notice of such suits on monday 
such a suit in us district court would seek an order requiring 
epa to perform duties spelled out in the act said the federations 
water specialist eric olson 
the federation released an agency audit of socalled 
noncommunity systems carried out by epas inspector general the 
inspector general in 1986 and 1987 checked water enforcement 
programs in virginia maryland pennsylvania and west virginia where 
an estimated 3 million people were using those systems 
epa officials said in the report they believed those four states 
were representative of the nation which has 150000 noncommunity 
water sources serving 36 million people 
state personnel in west virginia estimated that 40 percent of 
their noncommunity systems were out of compliance the report 
said the numbers were similar for pennsylvania 40 percent in 
fiscal year 1986 and 29 percent in fiscal year 1987 the federal 
reporting data system indicated only 7 percent of the noncommunity 
systems in virginia had monitoring violations in fiscal year 1987 
however our review revealed that these numbers were substantuially 
understated 
for coliform bacteria to be checked every three months unless 
otherwise specified by the state the report said the state of 
maryland estimated that 90 percent of the noncommunity systems 
did not comply with federal testing requirements 
in the document epa officials said the shortcomings were a 
direct function of epas longstanding policy to place priority on 
assuring compliance by community water systems 
noncommunity systems have looser testing requirements than 
community systems but even those were being ignored the report 
said 
in 19711985 the centers for disease control was able to trace 
to noncommunity water systems 45 percent of 484 outbreaks of 
diseases carried by drinking water 
an epa spokesman did not immediately return a telephone call 
seeking comment on the report monday 
the epa comments in the document said the agency planned priority 
attention in the fiscal year beginning next oct 1 for the 20000 
noncommunity systems serving groups other than travelers and 
will also consider requiring state and regional epa offices to 
meet quotas for enforcement actions 
a noncommunity system might be a single well serving a school 
factory restaurant motel or campground more generally it is any 
system serving transients or nonresidents including supplies on 
buses trains and planes even though those might get their water 
from public systems 
suppliers are supposed to post public notices when testing 
discloses a violation of standards but we found only 11 of 826 
monitoring violations had evidence of public notification in the 
file the auditors wrote state personnel admit that followup 
on public notification requirements is inadequate 
in some violations repeat testing is required to ensure that a 
standard is being met out of 145 violations of concentration 
standards that were checked repeat sampling was required in 98 but 
only in two instances did the supplier initiate check sampling 
within the required 24 hours we found no evidence of any check 
sampling at all for 28 of the 98 violations in the remaining 68 
instances the supplier delayed the initiation of the check sampling 
process for periods ranging from two to 37 days the report said 
pennyslvania and virginia issued notices of violations to 
suppliers in only 173 cases out of 371 cases in which notices should 
have been issued and 56 percent of the notices were issued two 
months or more after the end of the quarter in which the violation 
occurred the report said 
maryland and west virginia were not reporting what enforcement 
actions they took but the auditors found only seven notices to 
suppliers out of 600 violations 
the states have primary responsiblity for enforcing the federal 
law except indiana and wyoming where epa is directly responsible 
in addition the agency is directly responsible for enforcement on 
indian reservations and in the district of columbia 
</TEXT>
