<DOCNO> AP881212-0147 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
most family doctors are inadequately trained to 
recognize and treat illness that stems from unhealthy environments 
at home or work a national academy of sciences panel said monday 
but rather than criticizing individual physicians the report 
from the institute of medicine committee said the fault lies with 
our highly sophisticated health care system in general because 
it is not geared toward preventive medicine 
lacking a solid foundation in occupational and environmental 
medicine as well as in the related disciplines of epidemiology and 
toxicology most primary care physicians are hardpressed to keep up 
with developments in the field the report said indeed the 
general medical literature contains relatively little about 
occupational and environmental medicine 
to counter that the panels most urgent recommendation was for 
establishment of a clearinghouse for doctors to call when 
confronted with a patient suspected of having an occupational or 
environmental disease 
it should be designed so that a single telephone call satisfies 
the practitioners informational needs the report said it 
could be based on an extension of the techniques used by the 
nations poison control centers 
the institute of medicine a branch of the national academy of 
sciences is forming a new advisory committee specifically to draw 
up more detailed suggestions for such a clearinghouse 
on a longer range the panel that turned in its report monday 
said physician fee schedules should be changed because the current 
procedureoriented reimbursement system and the emphasis on 
efficiency of practice is antithetical to the desired emphasis on 
prevention 
eventually the committee said the focus must shift to medical 
schools only half of which have a single faculty member primarily 
concerned with occupational health 
occupational and environmental medicine should be a vital part 
of the traditional student clinical assignments the report said 
because preventative medicine is usually not taught in the 
clinical years it is necessary that departments of clinical 
medicine include occupational and environmental medicine as part of 
their third and fourthyear teaching programs 
the report also called for more research into occupational and 
environmental medicine 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

