the reagan administration renewed its offer 
monday of a substantive dialogue if yasser arafat the chairman 
of the palestine liberation organization explictly recognized 
israel and renounced terrorism 
the offer was made by the state department on the eve of arafats 
arrival in geneva for a un general assembly debate on the conflict 
between israel and palestinian arabs the session was shifted to the 
swiss city after secretary of state george p shultz blocked a visa 
for arafat to speak in new york 
shultz cited the plos terrorism record and called arafat an 
accessory he invoked a us law denying entry to terrorists as 
superseding a us agreement with the united nations to facilitate 
travel for foreigners to attend un sessions 
at the same time though shultz called palestinian participation 
in any mideast peace talks essential he also invited arafat to 
agree to three us requirements that must be met before the 
administration will hold diplomatic talks 
these are acceptance of un resolutions 242 and 338 adopted by 
the security council in 1967 and 1973 recognition of israels right 
to exist and renunciation of terrorism 
the two resolutions implicitly recognized israels right to exist 
within secure boundaries the palestine national council the 
legislative arm of the plo last month approved holding mideast 
negotiations within the framework of the resolutions but did not 
accept the resolutions directly 
in another move the council edged away from advocating 
terrorism but l paul bremer who directs the state departments 
office of counterterrorism said it did not amount to renouncing 
terrorism bremer referred to a reaffirmation of palestinians right 
to resist the israeli occupation of their land in any way 
possible 
and the plo group did not directly recognize israel 
weve put forward some very clearcut requirements which are 
necessary to satisfy to enter into a substantive dialogue with the 
plo charles e redman the state department spokesman said we 
look forward to the day when theyll do that step up to bat 
the us official called the three requirements a set of 
criteria and said when those criteria are satisfied when 
those conditions are met we are prepared to engage in a substantive 
dialogue 
still redman left unclear whether the united states would 
immediately deal with the plo if arafat met the three us 
conditions in geneva 
i dont want to predict what will happen he said we have 
to make a judgment when and if those three things are addressed 
