a federal judge monday refused to stop random 
drug testing of uniformed secret service agents but did not rule on 
the constitutionality of the program 
us district judge thomas flannery denied a motion by a public 
employees union for a preliminary injunction noting that other 
courts have refused to halt ongoing drugtesting programs while the 
question of their legality is still pending 
flannery did not rule on the merits of the challenge saying he 
would issue an opinion within a week but the judge indicated during 
a hearing that he might treat testing of police officers differently 
than regular civilian federal employees 
the random drug testing was challenged by 1013 uniformed secret 
service officers who guard the white house and foreign embassies in 
the nations capital the uniformed division officers association 
contends that the urine testing is an unconstitutional invasion of 
privacy 
just last week flannery barred the agriculture department from 
randomly testing 750 plant pest and animal disease inspectors 
saying there was no justification for invading their privacy 
flannery noted the inspectors did not carry weapons and were not 
considered law enforcement officials 
in that decision however flannery upheld testing of individual 
employees suspected of being impaired by drug use while on the job 
at mondays hearing flannery said the officers were part of a 
paramilitary force and had a reduced expectation of privacy stemming 
from their enlistment in the secret service 
they know what kind of work they are getting into flannery 
said they go into this job with their eyes open 
flannerys decision was hailed by assistant attorney general john 
bolton as recognition of the importance of ongoing drug testing in 
law enforcement 
