monday hope dwindled for people trapped in the rubble and the 
smell of decaying corpses filled the air 
other officials said rescuers working around the clock with 
everything from their bare hands to fiber optic cameras have pulled 
more than 18000 people from earthquake wreckage 
the work is not going badly but we would wish it to be more 
organized ryzhkov told foreign journalists at a news conference 
in yerevan the capital of armenia 
he also said many people died unnecessarily in wednesdays 
earthquake because poorly built houses collapsed into ruins we 
believe gross violations were permitted in designing and building 
the apartment houses that collapsed 
if the homes had been of goodquality construction something 
like this would not have happened ryzhkov said 
he said this view was shared by a government investigative 
commission and by president mikhail s gorbachev who visited the 
disaster area over the weekend 
pravda the communist party newspaper published a scathing 
article monday about scrapbuilders who constructed shoddy 
apartment buildings that crumbled into concrete and metal graves 
over victims who were buried alive 
health minister yevgeny i chazov estimated the temblor killed up 
to 60000 people ryzkhov said it was certain that 15000 had died 
but the figure would problably rise to 45000 
five days after the tragedy struck shelter and salvage equipment 
remained in short supply 
reporting monday from leninaken near the quakes epicenter the 
official soviet news agency tass said people wander among the 
debris of what used to be their homes straining their ears in the 
hope of hearing the voice of a missing sister father brother or 
simply any human voice 
soviet television showed a worker in kirovakan where 60 percent 
of the houses were destroyed bending a metal reinforcing rod in a 
collapsed concrete wall by hand his face strained with the effort 
another man moved mounds of broken concrete with a shovel 
a man and boy huddled over a fire in a small bucket their only 
source of warmth during what the television announcer described as 
five nights on a pile of rubble because there were not enough tents 
snow and temperatures of 1423 degrees fahrenheit were forecast 
boris shcherbina a deputy prime minister who directed the 
cleanup after the april 1986 chernobyl nuclear plant accident told 
tass in leninakan 
we shall work without letup to save everyone still alive under 
the debris even on the 10th and the 12th day after the disaster we 
shall work for as long as there is a chance to save the life of at 
least one unhappy victim 
he said more than 5000 people had been rescued in leninakan 
tass said 18500 had been saved in the entire disaster area which 
had a population of 700000 
but ryzhkov said at the new conference that only 5398 had been 
saved throughout the region he said 10 people were pulled alive 
from the rubble on monday 
associated press correspondent carol j williams visited spitak 
a city of more than 25000 before the quake and said the smells of 
burning and decomposing bodies were everywhere 
a british charity called international rescue corps said its 
14member team in spitak was using ultrasonic listening equipment 
and fiber optic cameras to locate survivors trapped under collapsed 
buildings 
more than 200 search dogs were helping and infrared devices that 
can detect the warmth of bodies trapped under rubble 
many of the nearly 1000 foreign helpers have said local 
officials are not organizing the rescue well and interpreters to 
help translate the many languages are scarce 
the second crash of a relief plane in two days was reported 
all seven crewmembers died when a sovietbuilt yugoslav military 
transport loaded with medical equipment and other supplies went down 
10 miles from the airport in yerevan capital of the armenian 
republic boris panyukov first deputy aviation minister made the 
announcement in moscow 
local reporters said the an12 cargo plane crashed before dawn 
because the pilot mistook a welllighted highway for a runway 
on sunday a soviet military plane bringing soldiers to help the 
rescue effort crashed as it approached leninakans airport killing 
78 people 
aid continued pouring in from abroad council of ministers 
spokesman lev voznesensky told the moscow news conference 38 foreign 
relief planes had arrived and the most six were from france 
george reid of the genevabased league of red cross and red 
crescent societies said in yerevan there was little hope of finding 
more survivors 
he said the only people still alive would be those who found 
water and air where they were trapped reid quoted reports that only 
150 people survived in spitak other reports say 10 percent lived 
meanwhile armenian activists said demonstrators fought with 
soldiers because several nationalist leaders were arrested 
one activist who avoided arrest raphael popoyan said by 
telephone three protests took place sunday in yerevan because 
leaders of the karabakh committee were arrested the committee has 
led a campaign for armenian control of nagornokarabakh a 
predominantly armenian region of neighboring azerbaijan 
he said soldiers and demonstrators fought during a protest near 
the railway station and several people were wounded an editor at 
armenpress confirmed the violence but said it did not appear to have 
been serious 
</TEXT>
