<TEXT>
panamanians are fleeing unemployment 
is rising the panama canal is suffering the american military is 
steaming and bank profits are falling 
about the only firm thing in panama is gen manuel antonio 
noriegas grip on it 
the country is going down the drain fast said ricardo arias 
calderon leader of the opposition christian democratic party 
he and ruben carles of the opposition newspaper la prensa said up 
to 40000 panamanians have left in 18 months unemployment is up 
from 11 percent in 1987 to 23 percent the treasury is in a bind and 
public employees went on strike demanding to be paid on time 
the us administrator for the panama canal says his job may not 
be turned over to a panamanian next year as required by the canal 
treaty and that washingtons antinoriega sanctions indirectly 
hinder operations at the canal which is to be turned over to panama 
at midnight dec 31 1999 
in recent months noriega has imprisoned critics changed 
election laws to make it easier for himself to run for president in 
may 1989 and closed four opposition newspapers including la prensa 
the opposition is reduced to receiving news by facsimile machines 
from the united states fax and photocopies the no 1 means of 
communication carles said in an interview 
panamas trip down the chute began in june 1987 with allegations 
that noriega rigged the 1984 elections laundered money and 
trafficked in drugs and arms 
relations with the united states traditionally close because of 
the canal took a nosedive last february when president eric arturo 
delvalle tried to fire noriega as head of the 15000member panama 
defense forces noriega had the legislature dismiss delvalle instead 
washingto refused to recognize the new president manuel solis 
palma and imposed economic sanctions in an effort to force noriega 
out 
six opposition parties recently signed a petition calling for 
noriegas ouster and formation of a transition government for 
panamas 22 million people 
they have not yet decided whether to enter candidates in next 
years presidential election nor has the general said whether he 
will run 
the people are scared to death carles said how can we 
have elections if everything is under noriegas control 
repeated calls were made to noriegas spokesman maj edgardo 
lopez and to leading members of the militarybacked democratic 
revolutionary party but were not returned 
banks closed for nine weeks last march and figures issued by the 
government indicated deposits at the more than 100 institutions 
operating in panama dropped from nearly 30 billion to just under 8 
billion 
us sanctions put panama in the same economic boat with cuba and 
nicaragua the other latin american countries on which washington 
imposed boycotts and compounded problems that began with the 
political strife 
this is one of the things that has really hurt the external 
image said edgardo lasso president of the panamanian banking 
association because the others are communist countries 
the government limited bank withdrawals putting a 100 ceiling 
on what could be withdrawn from savings accounts many panamanians 
stopped banking and sold certificates of deposit for less than 
market value 
noriega has taken up the timetested cry of cuba and nicaragua 
about a threat of imminent us invasion except that in panamas 
case about 10000 american soldiers already are in the country 
panama is headquarters for the us southern command and the 
soldiers nominally stationed here for the purpose of defending the 
canal use the strategic location for intelligence gathering and spy 
flights over central america 
officers of the southern command claim panamanian troops trespass 
nightly on us military facilities and have reported exchanges of 
fire in two dozen cases a us marine was shot to death by a 
comrade in april 
the goal is to embarrass the united states and raise the level 
of a sense of vulnerability a us official said 
the 1977 panama canal treaties specify that the troops must leave 
when the 50milelong waterway is turned over to panama but an 
accompanying pact requires the united states to assure 
indefinitely a regime providing for the permanent neutrality of 
the canal 
dennis mcauliffe administrator of the panama canal commission 
said the provision calling for a panamanian to take over his job at 
the end of 1989 is up in the air because the us president must 
approve the choice and anyone who bears the noriega imprint will 
never be acceptable 
mcauliffe said canal operations suffer somewhat because under 
the economic embargo the canal commission cannot pay its panamanian 
employees withholding taxes and the government has begun harassing 
workers for the money 
the fact is they are so nervous right now its affecting morale 
and that affects the efficiency of our operation said mcauliffe 
a retired army general 
