western port city for a formal celebration called koto hajime 
the beginning of things 
but since gang leader masahisa takenaka was killed by a splinter 
groups gunman in 1985 custom has forced the yamaguchigumi to 
cancel the annual ceremony because it has no top don 
takenaka was replaced by two men acting gang leader kazuo 
nakanishi and young leader yoshinori watanabe who led the gang 
into a war to avenge takenakas killing police say 
though that vendetta which has left 25 dead and 70 injured by 
police count now seems to be nearing an end police say the long 
time without a leader has led to factionalism in the gang weakening 
its pyramidstyle command structure 
public reaction to the highprofile violence has also plagued the 
gang japan has low rates of violent crime and very strict 
guncontrol laws but gunfights have brought attention to the gangs 
spawning grassroots movements to rid residential areas of gang 
headquarters and offices 
a yamaguchigumi subgang in the central japanese city of 
hamamatsu was in the media spotlight until public opposition forced 
it to relocate last year the gang is now on the verge of collapse 
according to ishii of the crime control office 
but masafumi ueda director of the office said in an interview 
that the public outcry and tough police crackdowns also may have 
worked to the syndicates benefit putting many smaller gangs out of 
business or forcing them to seek yamaguchigumi protection 
a recent issue of endless advance an inhouse journal 
published by the kyokuto shinseikai a large tokyo syndicate 
attested to the trend toward consolidation 
in the 120page edition obtained by the associated press were 
photos of top underworld figures gathered for dinner at a posh tokyo 
hotel to pursue friendly relations and cooperation and avoid 
intergang trouble 
technically the yamaguchigumi has only 86 members but each of 
the top 86 controls a network of subordinate gangs which in turn 
have their own kasa japanese for umbrella 
top bosses rarely face prosecution for serious crimes as 
underlings take responsibility sometimes even turning themselves 
in since doing prison time can bring a promotion 
according to an annual report by the national police agency more 
than 86000 gangsters in 3201 gangs are spread across the country 
roughly 40 percent belong to the big three nationwide syndicates 
the yamaguchigumi the tokyobased sumiyoshi rengokai and the 
inagawakai also based in tokyo 
ueda of the national police agency estimated total underworld 
income at the yen equivalent of 15 billion annually but he added 
that is only a rough guess 
yamaguchigumi income sources include gambling the protection 
racket fraud prostitution money laundering and narcotics these 
and countless other scams are backed up by front operations in 
construction the stock market and real estate 
police believe the deaths of hiroyuki watanabe and his boss 
kazuo kengaku an osaka stock market speculator are shadier 
examples of what the yamaguchigumi has done 
the bodies of the men who police allege had been kidnapped and 
held for ransom were dug up oct 18 entombed in a slab of 
concrete two yamaguchigumi affiliate members later confessed to 
the crime 
meanwhile kobe residents seem to accept the yamaguchigumis 
presence with a mixture of helplessness and inevitability 
ive never had any trouble with gangsters but i suppose id 
prefer it if theyd leave said a taxi driver the thing is 
youll never get rid of them 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

