<TEXT>
nancy marchand can speak with authority about 
very proper wasp matrons 
i know a lot of those ladies says the actress who grew up in 
an upper middleclass family in buffalo ny the way they lived 
is the way i lived 
proper is how many audiences view miss marchand too from her 
role as the nononsense wealthy newspaper publisher mrs pynchon 
on televisions lou grant to the befuddled mayor in this 
seasons surprise movie success the naked gun to her latest 
stage role an uppercrust matriarch with a fierce family loyalty in 
the offbroadway hit the cocktail hour 
the play written by ar gurney gets its title from that 
particular time of day usually before dinner when drinks and good 
conversation are served but in this case the conversation is not 
so agreeable 
a son has returned home to ask his parents permission to present 
a play he has written about them miss marchand plays the mother a 
peacemaker who tries to soften the generational squabbles and she 
walked off with glowing notices from the critics 
the actress has worked before with gurney who also comes from 
buffalo and from the same upperclass wasp society its a society 
gurney has written about before in such plays as the dining 
room the middle ages and the perfect party 
often when a playwright is writing a play there comes a point 
when he wants to hear it says miss marchand sitting in the 
living room of her upper west side apartment so ive done a lot 
of readings of his plays and when i read the cocktail hour i 
thought its the best play hes written 
the actress knew she had to play this woman and drew the 
character from her memories of other women her mother and even 
herself but dont ask her to explain how 
this is very hard for me to talk about because its all kind of 
subliminal she says with a laugh 
what i do is sit down right away and learn the role thats 
when i make a lot of discoveries about the character i get so 
involved that i become that person i know that sounds silly but i 
really do 
for miss marchand the cocktail hour has turned into 
particularly gratifying employment it will keep her in new york for 
a while for much of her career she needed to travel for work 
still she has managed to maintain what she calls a real 
household in new york it includes her husband actor paul sparer 
recently seen offbroadway as the father in the hit play a shayna 
maidel the couple raised three children now grown 
even when she was filming lou grant in california miss 
marchand was able to shoot most of her scenes in one day and come 
back to new york for the remainder of the week 
my husband was here and my youngest daughter was just finishing 
up high school she says this is my home but the producers 
were very good to me 
miss marchand also had the luck of appearing in what was a 
quality television show 
the topics that it dealt with were interesting and 
thoughtprovoking she says so it was a challenge for me 
so was the character in one episode early in the series run 
mrs pynchon had a stroke miss marchand recalls the illness gave 
her an opportunity to explore the character further 
she began using a cane for the role something she carried over 
to later episodes and then added other strokerelated 
characteristics to the womans personality like her having trouble 
remembering things 
for most of her career miss marchand has had to juggle family 
and career 
there were stretches of 12hour days when husband and wife never 
stopped running between family and career particularly when they 
both were members of the apaphoenix repertory company in the 1960s 
after working five or six hours rehearsing then rushing home 
and getting dinner on the table and listening to problems about 
trigonometry or getting kids bathed and ready for bed it cleaned 
out that period of time for me emotionally she recalls i could 
go back to the theater fresh and ready to do a show 
it was good for the children too 
it made them more independent and helped them get along 
together she says now they have left home and she can 
concentrate on her career 
i love the work so im not averse to doing something that isnt 
necessarily going to reflect my 35 years in the business she says 
a year ago she was klytemnestra in a production of elektra 
by ezra pound at a miniscule offoffbroadway theater for a 
miniscule salary if it interests me ill do it 
right now she still is fascinated by the cocktail hour 
striving to make the production and her performance better 
although its a play of language its economical she says 
because language is so specific you cant fool around with the 
words changing them or changing the syntax because you will change 
the rhythm and often change the meaning that is the hardest thing 
to do to get the words absolutely perfect 
the woman i play is very smart about dealing with the rhythms 
of the family miss marchand says quite early on in the play 
she says i want to know what i missed and discovers what she 
missed was not very good so she immediately drops it and then picks 
up and approaches it from a totally different point of view but 
its all done i hope as smooth as silk she calms the waters 
