<TEXT>
with tension high the countdown 
clock for the launch of space shuttle discovery ticked down to nine 
minutes and then was stopped deliberately to be held there for 10 
minutes while one man made the critical decision on whether to 
proceed toward liftoff 
this was no ordinary countdown it was to be americas first 
shuttle flight since the challenger explosion killed seven crew 
members 32 monthsture of the us space program was 
at stake 
memories of that tragedy were earlier the fu on everyones mind as 
five 
astronauts boarded discovery on the morning of sept 29 
one of the astronauts own navy capt robert crippen a veteran 
of four shuttle missions had the awesome responsibility to make the 
decision that would send them on their way or keep them on the 
ground for another day 
crippens assignment was a product of challenger no one man held 
sole authority to say go or nogo on any of the previous 26 
shuttle launches 
nasa decided it needed such a launch czar to avoid the 
communications failures that prevented the concerns of lowerlevel 
engineers about cold weather from reaching those making the decision 
to launch challenger the frigid temperature was cited by 
inve 
two months later the count reached nine minutes on the second 
postchallenger mission again high altitude winds were a problem 
this time they were too strong but they moderated gradually 
throughout the morning 
crippen looked at the latest data and made his decision 
dispatching atlantis and five astronauts on a secret defense 
department mission during which they reportedly released a 
sophisticated reconnaissance satellite it was another successful 
flight on nasas comeback trail 
the successes set the stage for a steppedup shuttle launch 
schedule in 1989 seven flights are planned including three 
scientifically prized missions that will deploy the hubble space 
telescope and dispatch payloads to venus and jupiter 
