<TEXT>
older adults generally do not have to give up driving because of 
aging changes in vision but they should recognize their 
limitations advises the american optometric association 
more than 37 million americans over 55 years old drive and 
according to the national safety council they have a poorer accident 
record than drivers in their middle years 
failure to yield rightofway improper lane changes passing and 
turning are among the most common traffic violations committed by 
older drivers national studies have shown 
according to the optometrists changes in vision may interfere 
with older drivers abilities to see and recognize what is on the 
road ahead to see effectively at night to see against the glare of 
oncoming headlights and to recover quickly from glare 
other factors include faulty judging of distances between 
themselves and other vehicles or objects and the detection of 
movement from the side while looking straight ahead 
suggestions from the optometrists on how older drivers can 
compensate for vision changes include 
avoid driving at dusk 
when driving at night reduce speed try to limit driving to 
welllighted or familiar roads and keep headlights taillights and 
turn signals clean and properly adjusted 
take time to adjust to a new eyeglass or contact lens 
prescription before driving 
avoid frames with wide side pieces that may block side vision 
wear quality sunglasses on sunny or bright cloudy days but 
never wear sunglasses or fashiontinted lenses when driving at 
night 
confine driving to places speeds and hours in which they are 
comfortable and competent 
avoid pulling off alongside the highway if necessary use the 
cars fourway emergency flashers 
keep windshield and rear windows clean inside and out and 
replace worn wiper blades promptly 
keep rear view and outside mirrors clean and properly adjusted 
be aware of their limitations 
</TEXT>
