<TEXT>
depending on where they work aging whitecollar workers face a 
job outlook ranging from crashandburn to a possible triple 
career ladder according to a study of 25 fortune 500 companies 
the state of the economy and the industry the company 
personality the nature of corporate leadership and the 
organizational structure were among the factors shaping company 
responses to the university of michigan survey 
all of these factors can change over time so you cannot lock a 
company into a particular behavior pattern says barbara hirshorn 
research fellow at the universitys population studies center 
it is clear however that a company under economic stress is 
much more likely to consider actions hurtful to older workers 
typical corporate responses indicated five distinct company 
policies toward elder employees those over 55 hirshorn notes they 
were characterized as proactive performancefocused at 
crosspurposes positive meansnegative ends and 
antagonistic 
proactive companies deal most effectively with older 
workers she explains planning strategies that build in options for 
workers at all ages as well as options for the company as a whole 
dual or even triple career ladders are not uncommon in 
proactive companies she adds they encourage lateral career 
changes and intentionally reassign workers at all ages to relieve 
boredom and stress 
hirshorn says performancefocused companies try to ignore age 
as a criterion altogether consistently applying a reliable 
evaluation system to all workers 
but occasionally companies are at crosspurposes in their 
policies she notes 
the company ethos may hold older workers in high regard and 
managers may even design some effective policies for them she 
says at the same time they are designing others that have an 
unfortunate effectthey dont coordinate policies and plan for 
change 
an example of such crosspurposes would be companies that offer 
limited opportunities for promotion or lateral moves and massive 
sweetened early retirement programs 
some companies are actively antagonistic toward older workers 
and the hostility shows up in a variety of policies hirshorn found 
i came across one insurance company where age bias ran deeply 
throughout the ranks she recalls those who refused to relocate 
were fired and since so few employees over 55 were promoted many 
older workers left 
