<TEXT>
spains major trade unions unhappy over the 
economic austerity of prime minister felipe gonzalezs government 
are taking to the streets to demand a bigger share in the countrys 
new prosperity 
a broad spectrum of society including autoworkers actresses 
soccer players and sportswriters say they will support wednesdays 
general strike called by the socialist general workers union and the 
communistdominated workers commission 
strike organizers say they want to bring the country of 38 
million to a standstill to force a change in the governments 
economic policies the unions also called for a demonstration on 
friday in madrid and said if the government does not respond more 
demonstrations will follow 
since taking office in december 1982 gonzalez has encouraged 
moderate wage increases to stem inflation prod economic growth and 
create jobs to cut spains 193 percent unemployment rate the 
highest in western europe 
due partly to lower wage increases backed in the past by the 
workers union spain has been booming since 1986 
more than 600000 new jobs have been created although growing 
numbers of youths and women entering the market have kept 
unemployment high 
annual inflation has dropped from 145 percent to 51 percent 
there have been reports of huge profits by spanish banks and 
corporations 
now the unions are demanding a share of the wealth for workers 
who sacrificed higher pay in the past few years to help pull spain 
out of a 10year economic recession 
the causes of the economic problems included the sharp rise in 
oil prices after the oil embargo of the early 1970s when spains 
energy needs were met by imported crude and protectionism under 
francos 19391975 rule 
what set off the strike call was the council of ministers 
passage oct 28 of a youth employment plan it allows businesses who 
hire 18 to 25yearolds for six to eight months at wages below the 
minimum to reduce their contributions to the government social 
security plan 
the government said the plan will create incentives to hire 
youths an estimated 40 percent of the age group have never held a 
job 
unions say the plan exploits young people benefits businesses 
and jeopardizes jobs and pay for older workers 
the nationwide general strike would be the first in spain since 
october 1934 when a leftistinspired work stoppage turned into an 
insurrection that was put down by troops commanded by gen francisco 
franco under orders from the thenconservative government of the 
second republic 
analysts do not expect violence this time but the feud between 
union leaders and top socialist party officials has taken on the 
hallmarks of a dramatic showdown 
nicolas redondo head of the general workers union has compared 
remarks from socialist party executive jose maria benegas 
criticizing the planned strike to comments by nazi propaganda chief 
joseph goebbels 
gonzalez in turn has accused the workers union of sliding 
toward the red falling under the influence of the more combative 
communist union 
when rightwing and centrist opposition parties with socialist 
support tried to pass a motion to urge the unions to call off the 
strike two small leftist parties voted against it approval 
required a unanimous vote 
newspapers described the incident as a sign of the 
ineffectiveness of the parties and parliament in breaking the 
uniongovernment impasse 
after uniongovernment wage talks broke down in the autumn the 
unions began accusing the gonzalez government of arrogance and lack 
of social sensitivity 
in a recent news conference gonzalez acknowledged that some 
arrogance could have creeped into his government but said this was 
no reason to stage a general strike 
</TEXT>
