<DOCNO> AP881212-0295 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
many business consultants make a very good living 
analyzing corporate weaknesses and devising fixup procedures that 
include new people equipment and processes 
much time is involved lots of money repeated conferences too 
computer reports and graphs prove the erudition of the 
consultants indeed if impressions were the measure of results 
these analyses would be invaluable 
contrast this complicated procedure with another approach 
championed by a respected consultant in which you focus on one 
problem or an aspect of one attack it immediately with existing 
talent and produce immediate results 
ive never seen a company in which it cannot be done says 
robert h schaffer who has written a remarkable book of common 
sense and canny insight buttressed by more than 25 years of 
experience 
while companies search far and wide for esoteric formulas to 
get them back in the running some very powerful solutions lie close 
at hand he says 
schaffer based in stamford conn has demonstrated his theories 
in big companies and small and now relates the story in the 
breakthrough strategy using shortterm success to build the high 
performance organization 
it confirms some widely held suspicions that management problems 
arent as complicated as they might seem that they seldom require 
the immediate purchase of new equipment and that they can be solved 
today rather than tomorrow 
overly simplified schaffer preaches resultsbased management 
development of which this is an example 
in january 1986 pennwalt corps headquarters informed wayne 
oquinn manager of its calvert city kentucky plant that a 
corporate study to evaluate the facilitys future was underway 
the reason costs of its key chemical products were overly high 
and its market was eroding after 37 years of operation the future 
of the plant and the jobs of its 400 employees were on the line 
seventeen improvement teams organized months before to tackle 
the plants myriad problems had failed to produce significant 
gains partly because their efforts were too broad now they sought 
to focus on one critical element 
the results showed up in just eight weeks they were able to 
raise by 20 percent the feed rate of raw materials into one kiln 
among the many used to produce chemical reactions success 
this first success changed the character of their turnaround 
efforts now they felt they could produce change the team moved on 
to other kilns with productive results then they moved on to other 
projects one at a time 
over the next six months the plants managers were able to reduce 
overall production costs by 18 percent focusing on one task at a 
time benefiting from the enthusiasm and confidence generated by 
their successes 
schaffer head of robert h schaffer amp associates is a devout 
believer in the principle that problems refined to their elements 
can be simple to deal with whereas problems taken as a whole can be 
impossibly difficult 
his approach is to get results at once utilizing the personnel 
and other resources already existing within a company why he asks 
does a crisis so often produce its own solution where months of 
earlier effort had failed 
why because a crisis produces a real sense of urgency a 
personal challenge to workers a sense of shared commitment to a 
welldefined goal a freedom to experiment with new ideas and a 
feeling of imminent success 
he calls them zest factors while he doesnt believe in 
creating artificial crises he does think it important to recognize 
the lessons that crises produce zest factors can be used to 
mobilize effective action 
in his book produced by ballinger publishing co a subsidiary 
of harper amp row he describes how initial successes become launching 
pads for a continuing process of improvement 
he asserts that companies can build their basic capacity to 
compete in the longterm while in fact because of obtaining a 
succession of small but immediate and tangible successes 
rarely does a business consultant offer you simplicity of 
approach low cost immediate results and a procedure for a 
continuing never ending series of improvements 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

